10_13	0.8	It helped make the year the hottest ever recorded.
10_14	1.2857142857142858	In addition to Rift Valley fever, El Nino has been linked to an upsurge in diseases ranging from cholera to malaria to dengue fever, in Kenya, Cambodia, Peru and other countries scattered around the globe.
10_15	0.0	Scientists are now trying to figure out how they can use this year's experiences to predict what the future will bring _ both in the next few months and in future decades.
10_16	1.2941176470588236	The good news is that they can now forecast an El Nino with some precision, and during El Nino years predict its effect on the world's weather months in advance.
10_17	1.9090909090909092	The bad news is that according to some research this latest El Nino might be a preview of the weather to come in the next century.
10_18	0.9545454545454546	In recent years, researchers have become better prepared for El Nino, thanks to the work of ocean modelers like Mark Cane and Stephen Zebiak of Columbia University's Lamont-Doherty Earth Observatory.
10_19	1.2222222222222223	In the mid-1980s Cane and Zebiak wanted a miniature Pacific they could play with, a simulation in which they could shut off this wind or that current to see which factors were most important to El Nino's existence.
